What is the Gospel? 

Matthew 4:23 👇🏾
“And Jesus went throughout all Galilee, teaching in their synagogues and proclaiming the gospel of the kingdom.”

Mark 1:14-15 4 👇🏾
“Now after John was arrested, Jesus came into Galilee, proclaiming the gospel of God, and saying, “The time is fulfilled, and the kingdom of God is at hand; repent and believe in the gospel.” 

Romans 10:9 👇🏾
“If you declare with your mouth, “Jesus is Lord,” and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved.”

The Gospel is simple. Jesus is LORD. That’s the Gospel.

Jesus. Is. King. 

Not Caesar. 
Not Herod. 
Not Nero. 

Not Cancer. 
Not Sin. 
Not Death. 

Not Depression. 
Not Poverty.
Not Trauma. 

THAT IS GOOD NEWS!!!

Jesus shares a throne with NO ONE. 

Gospel = the announcement of the good news that Jesus is King and His Kingdom shall reign forever. 

Let me know in the comments if Jesus is YOUR King.

Everyone wants Jesus as Savior. Nobody is turning down a “get out of jail free card” tbh. 

When we turn the Gospel of the Kingdom into the Gospel of the Cross we attract converts. 

However, when we preach the GOOD NEWS… the news that Jesus is King we make an appeal for men and women to surrender their lives to the Lordship of King Jesus and embrace a lifestyle of discipleship. 

Let’s make disciples. Not converts.

Paul was a follower of Jesus Christ. 
Paul obeyed the commandments of Jesus. 
Paul proudly declared that Jesus was King. 
Paul preached the Gospel of the Kingdom. 

The Reformed camp has co-opted Paul and tend to only interpret Paul through the lens of Martin Luther, John Calvin and other Reformers. 

That’s an injustice to Paul. Paul is not 15th century Reformer. Paul is a Jewish Rabbi who became convinced of the preeminence and Lordship of King Jesus.

Caesar was not happy about the Gospel message. Herod wasn’t happy about the Gospel message. Nero wasn’t excited to hear that there was some other King besides him. 

The Gospel of the Cross (which is only a part of the Gospel) is not offensive. However… running around an empire declaring that there’s a King who’s NOT Caesar??? Yeah. That gets you killed.

Your marriage matters more than your wedding day. Let me be clear. Your wedding day is vitally important. Can’t even have a marriage to emphasize without a wedding. 

However… I know people that spent tens of thousands of dollars on a DAY and they’re DIVORCED today. 

In the same way… I know people who used to identify as Christ followers who are currently DIVORCED from God. Maybe if we had preached the same Gospel Jesus preached we’d have more life long disciples of Jesus. 

Disciples > Converts 
Process> Moments 

Jesus Is King 👑

Matthew 2:1–3 👇🏾

“in the days of Herod the king, behold, wise men from the east came to Jerusalem, 2 saying, “Where is he who has been born king of the Jews? For we saw his star when it rose and have come to worship him.” 3 When Herod the king heard this, he was troubled

In the above passage take note of the way the word KING is used. The magi approach a king to tell him there’s another king. If you understand the context this moment is low key crazy and ridiculous. No wonder Herod killed every child under the age of 2… his position as king was threatened by the birth of Jesus. 

TWO KINGS CANNOT REIGN SIMULTANEOUSLY… 

The announcement of King Jesus means that every idol must be dethroned. That’s the power of the Gospel of Jesus.

Here’s the truth… WE ARE ALIENS to the world of Scripture. A failure to admit that is borderline arrogant. 

Context isn’t an “added bonus” or an accessory. Learning the context of Scripture is just as important as learning the content of Scripture because misinterpreting the Bible has dire consequences. 

I started @armacourses to teach ppl CONTEXT so that the CONTENT of Scripture begins to come to life. Learning context has single handedly changed the way I engage with Scripture. 

I challenge you to learn context too!
Family is everything. Love these humans more than anything. #ArangoTango 👊🏾

If you want to study the Bible then you will have to study history, language, culture, and CONTEXT! 

Content without context is dangerous. 
Content without context is confusing. 
Content without context is eisegesis. 

Only with CONTEXT can you practice proper EXEGESIS of Scripture.

Preaching the Gospel is not mainly concerned with CONVERSION MOMENTS… but rather a PROCESS OF SURRENDER!!! 

When we limit the Gospel message to God’s atoning sacrifice on the Cross we end up mainly preaching that message to non-Christians. 

However… Jesus preached the Gospel to the religious as well as the non-religious. 

Christians need the Gospel. 

Let me make it personal. I need the Gospel. I am constantly surrendering more and more of my life to King Jesus. 

So… for the Christians out there I have good news for you. Jesus is King. 

And for the non-Christians out there I have good news for you. Jesus is King. 

🤘🏾

You must be “Born Again” Nicodemus. Why? Because nobody is born righteous. Nobody. Absolutely nobody. 

We have ALL been born “this way” and by “this way” I mean IN SIN. 

If one day scientists find a certain gene that makes people act a certain way it will only confirm what the Bible already teaches - that from the womb we are deeply flawed and weak and broken. 

The invitation of the Gospel is to Born Again!

I could talk about the Gospel all day y’all! 

The Gospel is the announcement of the Kingdom. It’s an invitation to be a CITIZEN of God’s Kingdom. It’s an invitation to walk in wholeness. Reconciled relationship with your Creator and King. Reconciliation with yourself in the form of WHOLENESS. Reconciliation with others. And renewed connection to the ground from which we were taken. 

That’s the good news. 
That’s the Gospel. 
Jesus is King.

Sin is a complicated topic. And oversimplifying what sin is leads to unnecessary shame and guilt. The word “sin” can sometimes be weaponized to make ppl scared of going hell. Unfortunately there are so many examples of brokenness where ppl need healing and if the word “sin” brings shame they won’t seek out healing. 

Sin is brokenness. 

The Gospel of the Kingdom leads to healing and wholeness. 

I could write so much more. However I’ll simply challenge us to embrace a more nuanced and empathetic definition for sin that doesn’t lead to shame and guilt and actually leads to healing. 

The Gospel is God’s answer to ALL brokenness. Even the areas of brokenness that we wouldn’t immediately label as “sin”
